Various commentators have thought of a prisoner led by his captor, an animal led to sacrifice, a rope wound round a windlass, a tow-rope, the ‘tug of war.’ As tortus is a standing epithet of a rope (Virg. Aen. 4. 575; Ov. Met. 3. 679; Pers. 5. 146), no special force need be assigned to it here: hence the first or second view is the simplest.
